  <discussion>Henicodium geniculatum has mostly simple, erect secondary stems, and leaves with single costae. The margins are recurved throughout, and the laminal cells are 1-papillose. The species may be distinguished from Pireella by its leaves that are appressed when dry and spreading when moist (rather than little altered when dry), and laminal cells papillose over the lumina (rather than smooth or prorulose). Henicodium seems most often confused with poorly developed specimens of Pseudocryphaea domingensis; that species has a percurrent costa, laminal cells much wider and usually smooth, and no axillary gemmae but, usually, conspicuous flagellate branches.</discussion>
